Electric vehicles are way over priced, limited range, the posted range is total BS by experts admission. They are susceptible to lightening strikes, which totals the  car. I don't want to have to pull a trailer with a generator in it just to get home if I decide to go camping around Priest Lake or Pond Orielle. Go on a road trip, when you refuel it takes 15 minutes and time to pee. Charge your limited range POS and it takes 4 hours, if you can find a place to charge. 
The technology is decades from being more than good for Urban run a bouts.

All the traditional automakers have been moving upscale in price for over a decade now. Some have basically stopped making sedans. It may come down to GM and China to supply the cars below that line. Remember when we didn't think consumers could afford cars over $30,000? Now that seems like the starting price.
Most Automakers have already invested billions in the switch to EVs and ICE vehicles are getting more expensive to build and parts are not getting easier to get. It's beyond tipping point.

Fu*k Tesla and it's predatory strategy. It's a moderately good electric car, no loss for India or Indians if the Tesla decides to move out. We don't need to bend over backwards to facilitate a hypocrite narcissist Elon and Tesla. 
GoI is absolutely on the right track, with the policies and subsidies. Now the important step is to build lots and lots of HV DC chargers absolutely everywhere. Once we have the infra the adoption will be phenomenal. And I see lots of companies trying to move in this direction.

I don't particularly respect Elon Musk for trying to bully India into changing import duties just so he can import fully built up cars into India, while pretending that he really only wants to build Teslas in India. Just build the gigafactory in India, Elon, and forget about importing the high-spec cars from elsewhere. Then you can sell large numbers of cars in India that the masses can actually afford. Even a 40% import duty is going to make Teslas very expensive for locals in India.

I have expertise in this field.  The part of the equation that is customarily left out in these kinds of conversations is the electrical DEMAND factor.   Usage is one thing; demand entirely different.  If (for example) you have millions of Americans arriving home at 5:35pm and all plugging their electric vehicles in at once, you will have a very serious DEMAND on the electricity supplier that will require quite a robust infrastructure to accommodate.  Parent companies of electrical suppliers like Georgia Power, Duke Power, etc. have known of this demand issue for a very long time but have done little to address it.  Even before EV's were considered at the magnitude they are today, these power companies (The Southern Company, for example) have been defiant in their disdain for controlling DEMAND for residential users of their services.  Time of Use metering systems for residential applications was a battle sorely fought with these providers to give home-owners incentive to save on electrical demand.  It's a long complicated story that most politicians want no part of considering they're battling companies like The Southern Company and their deep purses.   In short, there is practically no way our country is going to build a grid in just a few years that will handle the level of demand required to meet the requirements of commuters.  So either the 'plan' involves shedding commuters (or limiting the commute to work) or some other means of transportation will have to be implemented in order to control electrical demand.

Dear Yogiji,

 I recently came across your theory about electric vehicles (EVs) not being a value-for-money choice compared to petrol cars, and I wanted to share my perspective on the matter.

Firstly, you mentioned that the excess amount spent on purchasing an EV could be invested in the share market or mutual funds to generate good returns. While investing in the financial markets can potentially yield profits, it's important to consider a couple of points regarding your theory.

Nobody buys a car with cash: In reality, most people purchase cars through financing options such as bank loans or leasing. When you opt for a loan, the additional 5 lakh rupees you mentioned would add to the loan amount, resulting in a slightly higher monthly payment. In this case, your theory of investing the excess amount wouldn't apply directly since you are still required to repay the loan.
Where will the excess 5 lakh come from if you are buying it via a bank loan? If you are considering taking a bank loan to buy a car, the loan amount will cover the full cost of the car. In this scenario, there won't be any extra money available to invest in the share market or mutual funds. The loan repayment will be based on the total cost of the vehicle, regardless of whether it's a petrol car or an EV.
Additionally, it's important to note that evaluating the value for money of an EV extends beyond the initial purchase cost. EVs typically have lower operational and maintenance expenses compared to petrol cars. The cost of electricity required to charge an EV is significantly lower than the cost of petrol. Moreover, EVs have fewer moving parts and typically require less frequent maintenance, resulting in potential savings over the long run.

Furthermore, various governments and organizations offer incentives, tax benefits, and subsidies for purchasing EVs, which can help offset the initial higher cost. These incentives, combined with potential fuel and maintenance savings, can make owning an EV a more cost-effective option over time.

It's crucial to consider the broader picture when assessing the value for money of EVs.  The transition to electric mobility is gaining momentum globally, with advancements in technology and infrastructure further enhancing the viability and appeal of EVs.

I believe it's worth exploring the comprehensive advantages and disadvantages of EVs before making a judgment solely based on the upfront cost.

They are all drinking the Kool-aid, I'm not against EV, but no one has looked further past their nose on this. Just a few things, the majority of cars out right now, are driven by 2nd owners, ie used cars, and by mid to lower income people.  So a used EV that has its warranty run out and the battery pack fails is going to cost 15Kish to replace. (a used refurbished motor for a f150 today is 1500, to 2500 ) Those who can't afford a EV will pay higher fuel costs due to supply and demand of fuel, again middle class and lower income. My 2c, as a fellow Melbournian:
1. introduce a graded congestion charge, particularly for busy inner city streets during peak times.  Rates can start of as simple Red Amber Green (or similar), which motor vehicles are charged for using Red and Amber roads during peak, shoulder times. Congestion charges have worked quite well in places like London.

2. Introduce a energy transition levy, which is 100% spent on helping people electrify their lives: EVs, Heat Pumps, household PV and VPP batteries. This would be a tax levied on hydrocarbon use, effectively a carbon tax. So we could keep our big gas burners as long as we want to keep paying the energy transition levy, but the sooner we switch the sooner we stop paying it.

3. RBA TFF (Transition Funding Facility), where the RBA will provide a discount window for repo type loans for banks and financial to fund low interest loans for certified energy transition programs, specifically helping businesses and households pay for industrial heat pumps, PVs, EV charging infrastructure, community batteries. Yes I know that this would add inflationary pressures in a situation where the RBA has said they will do everything they can to eliminate inflation.  Nevertheless, I think that during this energy transition, the RBA should both increase it's inflation target to between 2-5% and keep up pressures on the cash rate as well as increased taxation to channel more resources toward into the energy transition.

Concept of opportunity cost is based on the fact that resources are limited,but have many alternative uses. Since every Factor is limited,they cannot be fully utilised in all uses. From point of view of society,utilising a resource for a purpose means that opportunity of using it in other use is to be sacrificed. Opportunity producing cost of a goods is that quantity of goods which we have to sacrifice. That cost which encourages resources in their present use is called opportunity cost. For example,if certain resources are utilised in production of two commodity - wheat and Machine and with similar resources wheat of worth ‡•´ lakh rupees and ‡•™ lakh rupees of machine can be produced.  Producer in this case will produce wheat rather than machine or for wheat ‡•´ lakh rupees, machine of ‡•™ lakh rupees has to be sacrificed. In this way sacrificed value of machine will be called opportunity cost of wheat worth of ‡•´ lakh rupees. üôèüôèüôèüôèüôè

A close friend farms over 10,000 acres of corn in the mid-west. The property is spread out over 3 counties. His operation is a "partnership farm" with John Deere. They use the larger farm operations as demonstration projects for promotion and development of new equipment.

"How do I get a 50,000+ lb. combine that takes up the width of an entire road back to the shop 20 miles away when the battery goes dead?"

Battery Electric Vehicles (BEV's) don't have nearly as much of a fire problem as gasoline and Diesel fuelled cars.¬†

The ratio is something like 1 in 100 car fires is in a fully electric car. Hybrid cars are not electric cars; they burn fossil fuel. Those are the ones with something of a fire problem, caused by their complexity and the fact that they have to problems of a liquid fuelled car with the small addition of potential flammability of a battery. But that risk of a fire is still very low; something like 12 in a million, according to some sources. (Fully Charged covered this, for example.) To narrow it down further, by far the most likely chance of a battery fire comes from hybrids with Lithium-Ion batteries manufactured in China by LG.¬†

Modern BEV's are transitioning to Lithium Iron Phosphate (LFP) batteries, which have a far less likely chance of catching fire. The most popular car in the world right now is the Tesla Model Y. It outsells all fossil fuelled cars. The Model Y Standard Range is the most popular Model Y, and it uses a battery made from LFP cells. 

Remember that the BEV fire risk is already way lower than that for conventionally fuelled cars, so the use of LFP cells reduces that risk even further.

There is a huge amount of misinformation being propagated by oil companies and some traditional car manufacturers such as Toyota which is designed to deter people from buying BEV's. One outstanding point is that EV's are newsworthy, whereas petroleum fuelled vehicles are not.mNews media are concerned primarily with clicks, views and sales. Truth lags behind profit, so an EV fire becomes a ripe field for harvesting in this regard.¬†

In contrast, it's noteworthy that the huge fire at Luton airport, in England, which destroyed about 1,500 vehicles, stopped flights and tied up over 100 firefighters for almost two days, whilst destroying a four year old multi storey car park which didn't have a sprinkler system, only made the news because of the amount of damage which was done, and the disruption it has caused. In a small footnote, it was mentioned that the fire started in a Diesel-powered Range Rover. Not in an EV. No mention is made of the number of motorway vehicle fires which happen almost invariably in Diesel and gasoline powered vehicles every day of the year in Britain.

Be honest; how many gasoline or Diesel vehicle fires have you seen or experienced? And of the now millions of fully electric vehicles on the roads, how many fires in them have you witnessed? For most people, the answer to the second question is 'very few', or 'none'. I've seen countless liquid fuelled vehicle fires, and no electric vehicle fires. I've been in two vehicles which were on the brink of a fire, when fuel sprayed from a porous fuel hose or cracked pipe, onto a hot exhaust manifold. In both cases, the quick action of the driver saved the vehicle, and one of those incidents was with my own car. I've also helped to save another gasoline fuelled car which caught fire whilst being serviced. It took a team of people to keep it more or less under control until firefighters arrived with the proper equipment. The car's on board fire extinguisher was completely ineffectual.

As with all things in life, the emotive or unusual things grab our attention, and news outlets know that, to their advantage. But a balanced view is needed at all times if we want to understand life as it really is.

This is how the media spins a very serious subject into an inert issue. 
Electrical fires are generally heat related, and usually the result of high resistance relative to electrical connections. 
Each time a circuit connector is used, it heats up, it only takes you picking up your cell phone while its charging from a deep discharge to understand that point. 
However, if you eject a CD from your vehicles CD player after 30min to 1 hour of its use, you will also understand the heat being generated inside your cars radio, while playing that CD. 

So what happens as circuit connectors heat up and cool down over several cycles?    The answer is simple,  they tend to relax, creating a larger and larger gap between the connectors.  The larger the gap the higher the resistance and the more amperage required to make the connection.  More amperage equates to higher heat and eventually .... heat so high it becomes a source of ignition. 

Inside an EV battery there are lots of connectors.   Most of these connectors are copper since the atom structure of copper is very conducive to electrical current flow.  The downfall of copper however, is that it tends to deform under high heat,  When connectors deform, they cause resistance, that resistance causes temperatures to soar when attempting to supply current for the vehicles propulsion systems and other electronics.   This high temperature can cause the copper bits to glow and therefore become a fire source.  The worst condition for an EV would be where the battery has been continually drained for a long period of time, and the further the demand for amperage at low charge rates, the higher the heat will become.   Parking your EV after a nice long run, especially in the rain, they parking it in your garage over night, allows the batter temperature to continue to rise. if the liquid content of the battery starts to boil, then the battery will likely catch fire. This is know historically as heat soak, and although it happens to gasoline vehicle engines, the contents of the heat soaked components are not likely to catch fire. 

The reason we don't see many fires relative to hybrid cars is because power for the vehicle is supplied via a gasoline generator and not specifically from the battery pack. Further, with hybrid vehicles, parasitic devices (power steering, Air Conditioning, etc) are operated as a component of the gasoline engine.  Therefore they don't place undue stresses on the battery pack. 

So, if you own an EV, and you have drained the battery at or past 1/2 its maximum charge, you might want to think about, ways you can cool the battery pack down prior to either parking it in the garage or charging it for the evening.  The other consideration would be to not allow your EV to discharge at a rapid rate, and never allow your EV to loose more than 35%-40% if its full charge without recharging it and letting it cool down fully, before reusing it.  
The whole idea is relative to heat, and a discharging EV battery generates quite a bit of heat.   If you really want to know how hot your EV battery gets, acquire a simple thermometer which measures via infrared, and  test the battery pack temp for the vehicle when its fully charged and hasn't been operating for a few days.   Then make note of the temperature after you have used it normally.    Your alarm bells should go off if you find the battery temperature at or exceeding the boiling point range.   

Where gasoline engines and their related counterparts will operate at 195 deg F, that's a normal operating temperature and all components are designed to operate at that temperature, without failure.   EVs however don't generate heat due to combustion, they generate heat due to current flow, and as of yet, I have not observed an EV which indicates external and internal battery temperature, nor data which indicates the acceptable range of either.

Hello Gagan, very interesting video and you bring up some valid points. I am a Nexon EV user from past one year and just want to point out some valid counter arguments to some of the points mentioned in your video:

1) Insurance coverage : You are right in stating that insurance don't cover 100% battery and this is due to fact that we don't have any company issuing a separate policy wording for electric vehicles and they use that same ICE policy where 50% coverage point mentioned for all or most insurance providers. I had the same concern before purchase so raised this to Tata Motors team and they contacted all insurers using their inhouse insurance team. Based on that they sent a contact with email confirmation that few insurers will provide 100% battery coverage if Zero Dep policy is taken and from these i went ahead with Future Generali who gave the full battery cover plus a very nominal rate of insurance. I believe soon as the number of electric vehicle increases we will have insurance providers providing tailor made policies with such 100% battery coverage.

2) EV's are more polluting than ICE vehicle due to mining of rare earth metals and how electricity is produced: I don't want to mention any counter arguments but want to highlight another video from Youtube. I have been an EV owner for the past 5 months after thorough consultation with Gagan sir. I am primarily a big city driver in B2B traffic. And with experience, here are my inputs on the 5 points:
1. Range anxiety
Yes, it exists and there's no denial to it. Doesn't the same exist in ICE? If the fuel reading nears zero, it will make you rush to the nearest pump, wait in long queues and sometime fill them up in bottles due to poor planning. I can rest assured without worrying a petrol pump closure late at night or because of strike, as I can charge anytime at home.
Another big anxiety for ICE owners is "fuel price anxiety" that becomes talk of the nation every so often. A jump of 25 paise makes everyone jump, doesn't happen that with EV.
2. Battery
Yes, it's a major cost consuming factor. And like all things electric, this also needs proper care to be used. And so do ICE vehicles. Most EV batteries come with 8 years warranty, way above the standard 1 year on ICE engine (extendible to 3 years) or 1.5 lakh kms, which is again more than ICE. And call it to protect battery or what, EVs are very robustly build and safe in a casing that protects it even in cases of full frontal collision. How many ICE cars boast that?
3. Leg room
Yes, it's average. I have a sub 4 meter car, and rarely does a car give comfortable long time seating in this range. Precisely why on a long drive, one should get off for an hour while your legs rest and car gets charged ;)
4. Go green
Earth metals do contribute to pollution, and so does any extraction from earth: be it metals for engine, and it is well known that fossil fuels are the biggest contributors to pollution.

Range anxiety is one of the primary factors that limits any purchase of EVs, regardless of brand. Addressing the differing standards in charging interfaces may help in the short term regarding better access to EV charging stations, however I believe that EV manufacturers and electrical suppliers need to look at another option which eliminates a physical charging interface altogether.

Just as some cell phones and other electrical devices can be charged/powered using induction coils, surely that technology can be adapted to work somehow with EVs. Burying coils under pavement in parking lots, or even in some roadways could provide a useful alternative to specific park-and-charge locations that will likely get overwhelmed with visitors as EVs become more prevalent.

Isn't it something that the Lithium spot prices shown when this video was shot has gone down by 64% as of the writing of this comment. Similar to the great Silicon price explosion of 2004 through 2008, when it went from $17 to $475 only to crated to $60 within a year, and back to below $17 in two. That's right -- sand and coal had shot up that much just because of traders and perceived demand vs production. Are sand or coal rare? Well, neither is Lithium. It has gone from the 50th most abundant element on earth in 1990 to around the 20th most abundant just 30 years later, simply because so much more exploration has gone into finding it. Pretty much anywhere where Sodium (salt) is found, there is Lithium. 

And there are tons of mines going up all over the world. Australia, the world's top producer, has stated that 32% more Lithium will come to market this year, 2023. Plus the pressure of Sodium batteries going into mass production this year, where it will soon displace Lithium for all stationary storage.

Looking at the overall life cycle of my 2014 Leaf, it is clear that it has become greener since it was new 9 years ago. The grid on which it has been charged has more renewable electricity today, and is now over 94% emission free. A new battery recycling facility is being constructed just blocks from my home which will supply raw materials to a new battery manufacturing facility 2 hours down the road. Contrast this with the one or two battery manufacturing facilities that existed 9 years ago, and zero recycling facilities, and it is easy to see how the supply chain is improving, and will continue to improve as the EV market grows. My car, BTW, is in excellent condition and will likely give me another 5 years of use on the current battery, and thanks to the reliability of electric drive trains, can provide years more if I decide to replace the battery when the time comes.

Battery changing stations (using the infrastructure of the old gas stations) can help here: You'd drive around town with a small battery package, then, when you want to go on a journey, you'd get the bigger, extra battery package at the changing station. When arriving at your destination, let's say, Italy, you'd bring the big battery to the next changing station and drive around (if needed) with you small, fixed battery. On your way back, the same vice versa. We'd all only need small batteries in your daily lives, but could go on journeys easily. 
The only problem are - again - the car makers, who don't care about sustainability and practicability, instead of all agreeing on a very small number of battery sizes and dimensions. It has worked with the old lead batteries, hasn't it? They all have the same dimensions, you can buy them at many automotive parts stores, nobody thinks this is too much asked of them.

The shortages are at least partly due to bad planning, and deliberate reticence on the part of some legacy car manufacturers. Several are claiming that there is a shortage, and thus giving themselves an excuse for restricting the supply of EV's. The Chinese EV manufacturers are not complaining about shortages, and neither are Tesla. BYD has trebled its monthly output of EV's over the past 12 months and plan to do it again next year. We're looking at them producing 300,000 electric cars in a month, and making many of their own batteries.

It's worth noting that president Xi has issued an order in the past couple of weeks, forbidding Lithium producers from price gouging; raising the price of the metal to about 18 times its level of two years ago. If he has issued that decree, then he knows for certain that suppliers are being far too greedy, and that it is causing the roughly 100 Chinese EV manufacturers to sell their cars at a loss, in an effort to remain competitive. This has meant that only two companies which produce EV's in China are making a profit, namely Tesla and BYD. BYD are making only a slim profit.

Maybe it was too early, but you also made no mention of the new Sodium/Lithium hybrid batteries, which have almost the same energy density of Li-Ion batteries, and about the same energy density as Lithium Iron Phosphate (LFP) batteries. Both of those types are being improved steadily, but Sodium has the advantage that the cells are much more tolerant of both colder and hotter temperatures. It also has the big advantages of being much more abundant than Lithium, and being much cheaper to refine and use. After all, it's in every grain of common salt that you see. These new batteries are already being evaluated in prototype form in EV's. Results have been good so far, and there are definite plans to market lower cost EV's with this battery type. Estimates are that the new battery will cost about 50% of the price of Li-Ion batteries, and even undercutting LFP battery manufacture costs by almost 25%.

LFP batteries contain no Cobalt. Cobalt is also being reduced drastically in Li-Ion cells, with the aim of replacing it entirely, thus circumventing the dubious supply chain issues.¬†

Another development is the recently patented chemical method of extracting Lithium from ores, which can extract well over 95% of the Lithium, and could reach 99.5% extraction levels, at about the same price as the older methods. Less pollution is caused by this method. This technique also compares well against the most common methods of Li extraction which only recover about 45% to 50% of the metal. What that means is that formerly waste clays and ores can be reprocessed, to remove at least as much Lithium as was removed during the first processing, thus essentially more than doubling the amount of available Lithium.

for anyone interested, there is no elemental lithium in li-ion batteries, contrary to what some people might believe and what some simplified animations (like the one shown at the beginning of this video) might indicate. The lithium ions carry the positive charge, and the electrons carry the negative charge. However, they never truly recombine. They both join the anode/cathode (depending on whether the battery is being charged or discharged), where the electrons reduce/oxidise the the anode/cathode and the lithium ions intercalate into the anode/cathode (i.e. move into small voids within the electrode material). They remain ionized throughout the whole process.

edit: my pointing the oversimplification in the animation used in this video is not a diss in any way. I'm interested in natural sciences, but by no means an expert, and I think it's completely justified to simplify processes when explaining something to laypeople.

Are they less carbon intensive? They run on electricity that was produced in large part by burning fossil fuels. 
Furthermore, the electricity goes through several steps before it gets to the EV engine, the steps being the actual generation of electricity, which is 30-40% efficient, the transfer, which is 80-99% efficient, the voltage step-down/step-up, which is 95-99% efficient and is done at least twice, the battery charging, which is 60-85% efficient and then the discharging, which is 50-85% efficient depending on the driving style and temperature. 
All those losses without even taking the manufacturing of the vehicle and its battery into account. Some sources state that only 33% of the power generated in the US makes it to its destinations due to losses.
All in all, that comes out to an EV efficiency of 6.5% in the absolute worst-case scenario to 28% in the best-case scenario without considering the production of the EV.
A diesel engine burns diesel at 30-50% efficiency depending on the age of the motor. 90-99% of the pollutants (excluding CO2) generated in latest diesel engines are captured by emission control systems.
So, as long as our electricity is generated from fossil fuels, EVs pollute much more than a diesel car, just somewhere else instead of the tailpipe.

I'd like to point out that, even in the sodium-ion battery world, not all cathodes (and anodes) are created equal.

Faradion's cell technology apparently uses a sodium analogue of NMC cathodes, and still uses nickel in significant quantities. CATL are developing a Na-ion battery which apparently uses a 'Prussian blue analogue' cathode, using iron cyanide, which compares to Faradion's chemistry in a similar way to LFP and NCM in the Li-ion world (lower energy density, longer lifespan, more commonplace raw materials).

Na-ion uses 'hard carbon' anodes. Rather than an organised graphite structure, hard carbon is an atomically-disorganised mess. This is actually a good thing, and Na-ion can use lower-grade carbon that's basically scrap charcoal. But this is just one of many supply chain complications - where do you source thousands of tons of hard carbon from? Where do you source thousands of tons of high-purity sodium carbonate from?

Na-ion is a great technology, but it's got a hill to climb that's just as steep and slow-going as Li-ion.

As a car alternative, micro mobility uses 1/50th of the batteries of an EV car, consumes 1/10th the energy per mile and costs 1/20th the price - obviously an e-scooter, e-bike or e-wheel can't replace a car, but for a single occupant journey, it can displace an existing gasoline vehicle 80% of the time, without needing the consumer to buy a brand new car, an 80% reduction in emissions for 1/50th the amount of batteries needed for a car seems like an obvious solution for people who want to do this - it should not be illegal, it's a far more scalable solution than everyone buying a 70kWh EV to have it sit parked all the time.

There does need to be a deeper dive on car alternatives, and I think personal electric vehicles need a new look from Fully Charged, you've done a couple of light touch episodes, but the ridiculous situation in the UK of allowing drunk scooter rentals while fining and seizing responsible commuters is something I would like to see covered.

I am surprised the design of more efficient EVs was not mentioned as one solution. High efficiency designs, including lighter weight, lower drag coefficient, simplified drive train and even solar-assist could reduce battery pack size while yielding the same range. For example, the upcoming Aptera uses only 100Wh per mile as compared to SUVs and trucks that use 600-700Wh per mile requiring larger & heavier battery packs. Aptera gets 250 miles range from a tiny 25kWh battery pack, 400 miles from a 40kWh (about half the size of today's EV models). Also its solar-assist provides up to 40 miles/day of "free" propulsion. That's over double my daily commute, which means I may never have to charge until a long trip. I just reserved one.

What this really shows is that we can't afford to keep building these big EVs with big batteries. There simply isn't enough batteries for this. The key word that's going to blow up in a couple of years for EVs is going to be this : Efficiency. And if you want to look at what EVs should've evolved into a decade ago, look no further than the likes of Aptera.
The US govt incentivizes domestic  battery production and mining in the IRA, not mandates it. That's the take away for me. Incentives matter for EVs, e-bikes, e-trains...
Graphene is carbon! There is no shortage of carbon. Is a matter of time of upscaling graphene production. Aluminum graphene batteries will be possible in the near future.

I think this highlights perfectly that the current trajectory for renewable energy and EVs has not been thought through at all and is little more than a wish by those pushing for it. In order to reach net zero it is predicted we will need something like 1.5 petawatt hours of electricity storage globally and we currently have about 3.2 terawatt hours. There is no way this can be achieved, not even close yet our governments are still pushing this ruinous fantasy.
There is not enough lithium to make all the batteries needed to replace all the ICE vehicles. And no one is recycling lithium batteries. Ecological nightmare

We fix it the same way we fix everything: stop pretending society, humanity, & the world can continue under an overall operating assumption that we must constantly grow. We need strong public sectors. We need to produce what we need, & focus on living our lives with happiness that's not derived from stuff. With batteries, we need to stop the idea that everyone needs their own car, and that these cars need to be 2000 kg behemoths. We need massive investments on buses & trains. We need infrastructure and city development based on society, not individuals. We need to make public ownership of energy, its production, and the resources required to do it all.

Maybe the world needs to come to some agreement on configuration standardisation to reduce recycling costs & a commitment to used battery repositories to ensure that resource is not lost to landfill waiting for recycling operations to develop.

Disregarding weight for the moment, there are three figures that are important for motive batteries - total capacity, rate at which it can be charged, and the rate at which it can be DIScharged. Weight and bulk depend on the materials used. Some chemistry batteries are high capacity, but cannot deliver it fast, although they are good for a low rate for a long time, while others can deliver very quickly, at many times their 'C' rate, for a very short period. Finding the balance between the two is the tricky bit!

I think this demonstrates that EVs aren't the answer, they are a stop gap solution. But at least the world is looking at solutions more seriously.

1) Do note that this benefit is available only if you are using the car for your business purposes. If you use the car for personal purposes and still want to avail tax benefits, there are legal ways for you to be able to do that. We'll touch upon some of those ways in some other video.

2) You can also avail ITC of the GST that you've paid on getting Insurance and Warranty. This will further lower your cost.

3) For those select few people whose Output Supplies attract GST Compensation Cess, they can avail the ITC of "GST Compensation Cess portion in Ex-showroom Price of Car" too.

4) You don't have to be a Company to avail these tax benefits. Even an Individual can get this benefit by purchasing the car in their own name and using it for their business.
